00:05:19.710 --> 00:05:23.240
So everyone knows about Moore's Law.

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:28.979
It's not a law in the physical sense it's
an empirical observation about economics of

00:05:28.979 --> 00:05:30.370
chip production.

00:05:30.370 --> 00:05:38.160
In 1965, he looked at, Gordon Moore looked
at the trends in the production of chips and

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:42.720
he found that the component density was doubling
roughly every year.

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:50.370
In 1975, he revisited that because of changes
in the economics, the trend moved to doubling

00:05:50.370 --> 00:05:57.240
every two years and that trend in density
has helped for more or less the last 30 plus

00:05:57.240 --> 00:05:58.240
years.

00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:03.699
Now it's a characterization of the economics
of chip production not physical limits and

00:06:03.699 --> 00:06:05.990
it's often imprecisely cited.

00:06:05.990 --> 00:06:11.949
So for those of you who are interested in
understanding how this, the law as it's precisely

00:06:11.949 --> 00:06:16.879
stated, evolved over time, there's a great
article by Mollick in 2006 in the IEEE Annals

00:06:16.879 --> 00:06:19.280
that I heartily recommend.

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:27.539
So this is Moore's original graph and on the
Y axis, we have the relative manufacturing

00:06:27.539 --> 00:06:32.430
cost per component, on the X axis the number
of components per integrated circuit.

00:06:32.430 --> 00:06:37.770
Over time each of these curves is a snapshot
in a particular year and the minimum point

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:42.129
of this curve is the point of lowest cost
production.

00:06:42.129 --> 00:06:49.319
As you can see over time the cost per component
goes down and from the progress in the minima

00:06:49.319 --> 00:06:53.370
of these curves we get, what's now known as
Moore's Law.

00:06:53.370 --> 00:06:57.349
[Coughing in background]
