00:34:09.690 --> 00:34:13.860
You've got that five or six percent of direct
electricity used for computing, couple percent

00:34:13.860 --> 00:34:20.260
of that is data centers, but we also have
the other 95 percent which is being effected,

00:34:20.260 --> 00:34:24.450
in many cases, by the IT equipment.

00:34:24.450 --> 00:34:28.670
And you also have the rest of fuel consumption,
non electricity consumption, that could potentially

00:34:28.670 --> 00:34:30.179
affect it as well.

00:34:30.179 --> 00:34:35.770
So I think it's important to track the total
electricity used by IT, I think it's something

00:34:35.770 --> 00:34:39.169
I've done, you know, something I've done for
a long time, I think it's important to do

00:34:39.169 --> 00:34:45.110
but I think it's also important to try to
understand the effect of that IT on the rest,

00:34:45.110 --> 00:34:46.950
the other 95 percent.

00:34:46.950 --> 00:34:49.960
And that, to me, is the more interesting question.

00:34:49.960 --> 00:34:56.440
So one example that I did, that I worked on
recently relates to a trade-off between buying

00:34:56.440 --> 00:35:03.040
music on a CD versus downloading it and we
found that even in the best case for CD, sending

00:35:03.040 --> 00:35:08.800
a CD compared to the worst case for downloading,
that it was still a 40 percent savings and

00:35:08.800 --> 00:35:13.450
it's much likely to be in emissions, it's
much likely to be more than that.

00:35:13.450 --> 00:35:17.630
So I think that it's important to start to
do more and more case studies like that to

00:35:17.630 --> 00:35:22.340
understand these systemic effects because
direct electricity use, while it's more important,

00:35:22.340 --> 00:35:26.760
it's not something we should be getting very
excited about because it's, at the end of

00:35:26.760 --> 00:35:30.390
the day it's a pretty good use for the electricity,
in my view.

00:35:30.390 --> 00:35:35.790
And on the data center side, you've got, let's
just call it 90 percent of data center floor

00:35:35.790 --> 00:35:40.780
space is in house data centers in companies
whose main business is not computing.

00:35:40.780 --> 00:35:43.720
It's, in general, very, very inefficient.

00:35:43.720 --> 00:35:50.110
Utilization for servers of five to 15 percent,
a number of comatose servers not doing anything

00:35:50.110 --> 00:35:55.320
but still using electricity, 20, 25, 30 percent
of the servers.

00:35:55.320 --> 00:36:01.220
Huge inefficiencies there as there'll be a
shift more towards Cloud implementations there'll

00:36:01.220 --> 00:36:06.190
be actually a reduction, increase in the efficiency
of producing those services as a reduction

00:36:06.190 --> 00:36:07.190
in energy use.

00:36:07.190 --> 00:36:11.860
So there's a huge potential for improvements
in data centers simply by shifting towards

00:36:11.860 --> 00:36:14.440
a more efficient way of delivering the services.

00:36:14.440 --> 00:36:18.660
So there's a lot of moving parts in this but
you're asking the right question I just think

00:36:18.660 --> 00:36:23.340
the focus really needs to be on the other
95 percent and what the IT can be doing for

00:36:23.340 --> 00:36:24.340
that.

