00:37:19.290 --> 00:37:24.460
&gt;&gt;male #8: Have you looked at the delivered
computation as opposed to the computational

00:37:24.460 --> 00:37:25.460
efficiency?

00:37:25.460 --> 00:37:30.110
In particular what I'm thinking of is the
software efficiency, now, 20 years ago I had

00:37:30.110 --> 00:37:35.370
a Window Manager that was about as responsive
as the one today but it takes way more instructions.

00:37:35.370 --> 00:37:40.840
&gt;&gt;Jon Koomey: Yeah, so the question relates
to looking at software efficiency as opposed

00:37:40.840 --> 00:37:44.910
to hardware and this is to me, actually this
is a fascinating area because in the past

00:37:44.910 --> 00:37:47.690
we've mainly thought of performance as a question
of hardware.

00:37:47.690 --> 00:37:53.440
We said Intel will give us or AMD will give
us more performance, we just don't have to

00:37:53.440 --> 00:37:54.520
worry about our code.

00:37:54.520 --> 00:37:59.550
Well I think that's changing particularly
as the need for parallelism, you know, you

00:37:59.550 --> 00:38:02.500
have a lot of cords you have to change your
software that's very important.

00:38:02.500 --> 00:38:04.911
It turns out that there are big potential
gains there.

00:38:04.911 --> 00:38:08.980
There are some folks at LBL that have looked
at what's called code design of software and

00:38:08.980 --> 00:38:09.980
hardware.

00:38:09.980 --> 00:38:13.550
This is a term that comes from the embedded
system space but they're starting to apply

00:38:13.550 --> 00:38:18.750
into the super computer space because when
they came to Steve Chu when he was the director

00:38:18.750 --> 00:38:25.640
of the lab there and said our new super computer
is gonna use 200 megawatts and they said,

00:38:25.640 --> 00:38:33.390
Steve Chu said, "No, go back and redesign
it" and they started to look at ways to co-design

00:38:33.390 --> 00:38:38.300
the software and hardware and they were finding,
you know, tours of magnitude improvement in

00:38:38.300 --> 00:38:43.420
the efficiency just because they optimized
the software and the hardware together to

00:38:43.420 --> 00:38:45.180
attack certain kinds of problems.

00:38:45.180 --> 00:38:49.320
They were gonna see a lot more of that and
it's really true, I think everyone here has

00:38:49.320 --> 00:38:53.980
a story about, you know, we're doing the same
basic thing using a whole lot more cycles.

00:38:53.980 --> 00:38:59.420
And part of what I think goes on is that the
costs of inefficient code are not being brought

00:38:59.420 --> 00:39:04.920
to bear on the people who are designing it
and as soon as you can get to the place where

00:39:04.920 --> 00:39:10.300
someone selling data centers services is able
to give that information to the people using

00:39:10.300 --> 00:39:15.470
the services, when we get to that point, then
you're gonna start to see much more optimization.

00:39:15.470 --> 00:39:20.790
We're not there yet but you can imagine it
being done to technology that exists today

00:39:20.790 --> 00:39:25.120
and that's where I think we need to get to
so that people actually understand the true

00:39:25.120 --> 00:39:30.960
total cost of a computing cycle when they're
using it and then they'll change their behavior.

00:39:30.960 --> 00:39:31.960
